When doing a search in Windows Explorer, the main explorer pane is changed to a Search Results pane. Any navigation done in this window pane is still considered part of the search results. To view the search result folders in a normal explorer view which will expand the folders in the navigation pane, it is necessary to rightclick the folder in the Search Results pane and choose the Open folder location option.

Any combination of shipments or deliveries can be combined onto the same load as long as they are referencing the same carrier number. Pick list numbers and could have been, and probably should have been, combined onto one shipment as they had the same shipment specification number, which meant that all infomration in the VASPEZ table was the same between the two pick lists. However, pick list number should not have been able to be combine, and it wasn't. VSS did allow it to go on the same load since all pick lists were referencing the same carrier Hi John, the question is why shouldn't we. I checked the shipments and there is no reason to deny putting them in one load. A load is principally just a carrier. You put the packages on a carrier but you don't know how far it drives. For example If you make a load for three customers, the carrier can drive to a HUB and the divide it in three different carriers. Therefore it is allowed to put them together. Two issues were identified. The MES system does not appear to be updating EP as quicklyl as anticipated. There is nothing that this group can do about that issue. The other issue, however, appears to deal with how the system determines who should get the back to green emails. When presented with a workstation that changed its status to production', it would find the last event that was of type production', setup', or other downtime'. The back to green mail was sent to all user's that had been notified by the system between these two events. However, the stamping presses frequently cycle from a repair state to a setup state and then to production. In this situation, the software would not send any notifications since its last good state was the setup that preceeded the return to production. The system has been modified to only consider production as a valid previous state. With this change, all personnel that were notified of an issue between the current event and the previous production event will be notified that the workstation is back in production.

Group policy was not being applied to the machine and further investigation showed that no network resources were accessible. No UNC paths, no DFS paths, nothing. Machine was accessible on the network, able to resolve and ping network resources but simply unable to connect to the resources. Event log showed that the TCP IP NetBIOS Helper service was unable to start. Looking at the services on the machine, the service was listed but the description couldn't be found so this appeared to be the root of the problem. Uninstalled Client for Microsoft Networks from the NIC, rebooted PC, and the TCP IP NetBIOS service was properly removed. Reinstalled the client for MS networks on the NIC but the service wasn't returned. Further investigation showed that the lmhsvc.dll file in the system directory appeared to be corrupt information on the details tab of this file were missing. This file was copied from a working machine but service still didn't appear after a reboot. To restore the service, the HKEY LOCAL MACHINEkey was copied from a known working machine and imported to After rebooting the service was running properly.
